362-484. The pugilistic contest is next described. Dares, a Trojan, pre- sents himself as the challenges, but at first no one is disposed to compete with him. Then an old Sicilian ol Trojan descent, Entellus, is induced by his friend Acestes to enter the lists. They put on the gauntlets furnished by Aeneas, and begin the fight. Entellus at first stands on the delensive, and merely patries or avoids the blows of his more nimble antagonist. At last the old man aims a blow with immense ellort at Dares, who adroitly turns aside, leaving Entellus to fall headlong by the impetus ol his own motion. Entellus, thus roused by shame and revenge, rises from the ground, attacks Dares with fury, and gains the victory.
